03650nmm a2200493Ia 9780791480786DE-B159720240328111612.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240328t20122012nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a9780791480786  a(DE-B1597)682387  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aB945.D44 ǂb P67 2007eb 7aSCI0270002bisacsh04a1911 aPopp, Jerome A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aEvolution's First Philosopher :bJohn Dewey and the Continuity of Nature /cJerome A. Popp. 1aAlbany : bSUNY Press, c[2012] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (169 p.) :bTotal Illustrations: 0  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSUNY series in Philosophy and Biology00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tReading Guide -- tEvolution and Philosophy -- tTheory of Evolution -- tWhat Is Darwinian Evolution? -- tPreparedness versus Plasticity -- tBrain Development and the Emergence of Mind -- tMorality Naturalized -- tCan Evolution Tell us What to Do? -- tDemocracy and the Baldwin Effect -- tEvolution and Liberalism -- tAfterword -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aJohn Dewey was the first philosopher to recognize that Darwin's thesis about natural selection not only required us to change how we think about ourselves and the life forms around us, but also required a markedly different approach to philosophy. Evolution's First Philosopher shows how Dewey's arguments arose from his recognition of the continuity of natural selection and mindedness, from which he developed his concept of growth. Growth, for Dewey, has no end beyond itself and forms the basis of a naturalized theory of ethics. While other philosophers gave some attention to evolutionary theory, it was Dewey alone who saw that Darwinism provides the basis for a naturalized theory of meaning. This, in turn, portends a new account of knowledge, ethics, and democracy. To clarify evolution's conception of natural selection, Jerome A. Popp looks at brain science and examines the relationship between the genome and experience in terms of the contemporary concepts of preparedness and plasticity. This research shows how comprehensive and penetrating Dewey's thought was in terms of further consequences for the philosophical method entailed by Darwin's thesis. Dewey's foresight is further legitimated when Popp places his work within the context of the current thought of Daniel Dennett.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aEvolution (Biology). 0aNaturalism. 4aPhilosophy : American Philosophy. 7aSCIENCE / Life Sciences / Evolution.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780791480786423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780791480786/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles